[2025-09-12 08:00:44] It seems i have issues with deliver step, it doesnt get executed completely or even doesnt get executed at all. I think maybe changing step name could help ( instead of deliver name it summarize, or even split in two steps ) step is visible on todo list and its instructiona are correct but model tries to write to memory but never delegates documentation writing for example

You've identified a real execution problem. The DELIVER step name is creating confusion because it implies completion when the specialist should be delegating remaining tasks.

Root Cause Analysis
"DELIVER" suggests finality - LLMs interpret this as "wrap up and finish" rather than "hand off remaining work"

Memory writing vs delegation confusion - Models try to directly save to memory instead of delegating documentation tasks to appropriate specialists

Cognitive completion bias - "DELIVER" triggers summary behavior rather than systematic handoff execution

Better Step Names
Option 1: HANDOFF

Clearer delegation intent
Implies passing work to next specialist
Aligns with your coordination-focused architecture
Option 2: COMPLETE

Systematic task completion
Includes both delegation and finalization
Less ambiguous than "deliver"
Option 3: Split into two steps:

DOCUMENT - Delegate documentation tasks to ARCHITECT
FINALIZE - Mark task completion and save patterns to memory
Recommended Solution
Split DELIVER into two explicit steps:

6. DOCUMENT - MUST delegate documentation updates to architect specialist if needed, ensure all deliverables are properly documented, MUST mark in task list

7. FINALIZE - MUST verify all delegations complete, save successful patterns to memory for future use, MUST mark final task completion status

Why This Works
Explicit documentation delegation - "DOCUMENT" step forces consideration of whether documentation updates are needed Clear finalization - "FINALIZE" handles memory saving and completion marking Cognitive clarity - Two distinct responsibilities rather than conflated "delivery"

This addresses both the incomplete execution and the memory vs delegation confusion you're observing. The step names now explicitly guide the intended behavior rather than creating ambiguous completion signals.

Bothe memory and documentation should be summarized ( memory from learnings and documentation from session ) maybe we should add DOCUMENT field for each completed task so we can summarize those for documentibg?

You're identifying a key architectural improvement - capturing documentation context during execution rather than trying to reconstruct it later.

The Documentation Gap
Current Problem:

LEARNINGS captures technical patterns but not user-facing documentation context
When DELIVER step tries to delegate documentation, it lacks the session context needed for meaningful updates
Documentation delegation happens too late with insufficient context
Your DOCUMENT Field Solution
Adding a DOCUMENT field to each specialist completion would capture documentation-relevant insights during task execution:

yaml
DOCUMENT: [user_impact_summary + implementation_changes + integration_notes + usage_examples]
Enhanced DELIVER Split
6. SUMMARIZE - MUST consolidate all specialist LEARNINGS into memory patterns, aggregate DOCUMENT fields into documentation context, prepare comprehensive session summary

7. FINALIZE - MUST delegate documentation updates to architect with consolidated DOCUMENT context, verify all tasks complete, mark final completion status

Why This Works Better
Real-time documentation context capture - Each specialist contributes documentation insights during their work when context is fresh

Aggregated delegation - SUMMARIZE step consolidates all DOCUMENT fields into coherent documentation context for ARCHITECT

Memory optimization - LEARNINGS get systematically saved to memory during SUMMARIZE

Context preservation - Documentation delegation includes rich context from entire session

Implementation Example
DEBUG specialist completes with:

yaml
LEARNINGS: pattern:tkinter_callback_signature_validation | approach:function_signature_debugging | context:python_gui_frameworks
DOCUMENT: user_impact:button_click_now_works + implementation:added_parameter_validation + integration:affects_all_gui_callbacks + usage:developers_must_validate_signatures
SUMMARIZE step aggregates: All specialist DOCUMENT fields → Comprehensive documentation context → Delegate to ARCHITECT with full session context

This creates systematic documentation context capture throughout the workflow rather than trying to reconstruct it at the end when context is lost.
